0s and the twenty-first century. Offering insights that extend beyond Cuba, Humphreys reveals what happens to public debate when freedom of expression can no longer be distinguished from complicity while demonstrating the ways in which combining anthropology with film studies can shed light on cinema's broader social and political import.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszCuba. 0aMotion pictureszCubaxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszCubaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszCubaxHistoryy21st century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007142zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007142.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles